			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Has AE Kiting gotten easier??<a name="39318"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 10 04 7:19 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>PBAoE (Point Blank Area of Effect) Bard DoT's have a very LIMITED range. Before we could extend the range of these songs with AA, however due to our creative usage of these songs, SOE felt that we were overpowered. (Given, being able to kite 50 mobs at a time in HoH, even while taking almost twenty minutes of nerve wracking footwork, is a bit overpowering.) In order to combat this, SOE implemented two nerfs into the game. First they tried to go the simple route; they made a certain number of mobs in HoH summon, almost - it seems - at random. To no avail, this simply persuaded bards to pickup and leave HoH for other zones. Realizing this, SOE implemented one of the most controversial nerfs in recent bard history; they nerfed the range of AE DoTs as to not be affected by range extending AAs.
<br />

<br />
So, according to SOE, this problem was considered fixed, and Norrath should have been rid of pesky bards, kiting entire zones. But, we can still AE kite. However, due to OUR range being limited, the MOB's melee range must be limited as well. AE kiting mobs that are humanoid, non-casting, un-sow'ed, and small in size is still an available option. Humanoid warrior like mobs, that do not summon, and have melee ranges similar to that of a player character simply are SLIGHTLY out-ranged by our AE DoT's. So it is still possible to kite mobs like the ghosts in Natimbi, most of the zone in Dulak, most guards around old-world cities, and any other types that fit those requirements. It's not an issue of zone, era, or lunar alignment, but rather the specific type of mob described above. I hope this information proves worthwhile. 
<br />
</span></td>
